Welcome to my public github! Many of the projects I work on have code I cannot share at the moment pending research results, 
but I have included two examples here of the major projects I have worked on.

First is Spin_modelling_example, which is a very old version of the working notebook I wrote for my simulation projects with Eu5Sn2As6. 
It uses a model of magnetic exchange in Eu chalcogens introduced by T. Kasuya in 1970. This leads to two major ordering mechanisms; 
1. A ferromagnetic indirect exchange mediated by Eu-5d-mediated onsite hopping and 2. A distance-dependent FM/AFM superexchange mediated by 
As-3p orbitals in Eu5Sn2As6. My code models this by calculating the distance-dependent strength at each bond under a certain critical distance,
and then uses the gradient-descent minimize_energy! method from the SU(N)NY software to find a magnetic ground state, and then print it.

Second is some of the code used in my 2-qubit gate in integer GF fluxonium project. This notebook simulates a parametric iSWAP gate between 
two fluxonium qubits using an explicit SQUID-loop transmon as a third quantum degree of freedom in the Hilbert space, rather than treating 
the coupler as a classical control line. The two fluxonium qubits share slightly different g–f transition frequencies (~100 MHz detuning), 
and both are biased slightly off the integer-flux symmetry point so that the charge matrix element ⟨g|n̂|f⟩ is nonzero. A small AC flux tone 
at the difference frequency Δω_gf = ω_gf^(A) − ω_gf^(B) is threaded through the coupler's SQUID loop, periodically modulating its Josephson 
energy and thereby modulating the dispersive qubit–qubit coupling it mediates; when this modulation is resonant with the energy splitting 
between |gf⟩ and |fg⟩, it drives coherent population exchange in the g–f computational subspace. The simulation builds the full 
64-dimensional Hilbert space (4 qubit-A levels × 4 qubit-B levels × 4 coupler levels), diagonalizes the static Hamiltonian 
to identify dressed computational states via maximum-overlap with bare product states, computes the modulation operator 
∂H/∂Φ_c projected into the coupler eigenbasis, and integrates the time-dependent Schrödinger equation with qt.propagator; 
the resulting unitary is then projected onto the four-state computational subspace, single-qubit Z phases are analytically corrected, 
and the Z-corrected fidelity against the ideal iSWAP is returned alongside peak leakage into |ee⟩ and coupler-excited states.


